NexaSign — Enterprise features intentionally removed
=====================================================

Upstream Documenso ships a proprietary Enterprise Edition under the
"Documenso Commercial License" that provides the following features:

  - The Stripe Billing Module
  - Organisation Authentication Portal (SSO)
  - Document Action Reauthentication (Passkeys and 2FA)
  - 21 CFR
  - Email domains
  - Embed authoring (with white-label)
  - Enterprise-level support and SLAs

NexaSign is a pure AGPL-3.0 fork. The proprietary code for these features
has been removed and replaced with stub implementations (see the LICENSE
file in this directory). Concretely:

  - Self-hosted quotas: return "unlimited" for all limits
    (documents, recipients, direct templates, envelope item count).

  - Stripe: all billing / subscription / webhook / customer-management
    functions throw a clearly-labelled "not available" error if something
    still tries to call them. Since `IS_BILLING_ENABLED` is false for
    self-hosters, nothing in the normal request path should reach them.

  - Organisation Authentication Portal: the confirmation-email helper
    and the `linkOrganisationAccount` entry point are stubbed to no-ops.
    Ordinary login (email + password, OAuth) continues to work via the
    non-enterprise auth package.

  - Custom email sending domains: `createEmailDomain`,
    `verifyEmailDomain`, `deleteEmailDomain`, `reregisterEmailDomain`
    return sensible defaults but do not talk to AWS SES. Emails are
    sent through the SMTP transport configured in `.env`.

  - The tRPC `enterprise-router` still exists (to keep types stable
    with upstream) but its endpoints surface "feature not available"
    errors when called.

Anyone who wants these features in their own deployment has two paths:

  1. License the Enterprise features from Documenso directly
     (https://documenso.com/pricing), self-host Documenso proper, and
     port back the parts of NexaSign that appeal (GoBD tooling,
     X-Rechnung generator, German templates).

  2. Re-implement what they need under AGPL as new code inside this
     repository. Pull requests welcome.
